One refinement I’d make

I actually wouldn’t make the entire bag a giant patch wall.

Instead, I’d designate one or two “story panels”—laser-cut hook-and-loop fields that are beautifully integrated into the bag’s design. Most of the bag remains premium leather or technical fabric, while these panels become curated displays.

That changes the psychology.

It feels less like you’re covering your bag with decorations and more like you’re displaying earned accomplishments.

Think of it as the difference between a military dress uniform covered in carefully placed ribbons versus a backpack covered in random stickers.

That level of restraint makes the bag feel more premium while giving golfers a reason to keep collecting for years. I could genuinely see someone looking at a friend’s bag and asking, “Where did you get that Bandon patch?”—and that’s exactly the conversation that grows the ecosystem.